1. What you get from the Airtel cloud team (one‑time per environment / tenant)
Using CMP, they:

Create an F5 LB instance for your tenant

CMP automates:

Two F5 VMs (HA pair).
Connect them to:
Management network (for APIs),
VIP subnet (for external IPs),
Internal/data networks (to reach Seeds/Shoots).
On the VIP subnet, OpenStack gives 3 infra IPs:
self IP on VM‑1,
self IP on VM‑2,
floating self IP (for HA).
You don’t use these 3 directly; they’re infra.

Give you these details

After LB is deployed, they provide:

LB name (in CMP).
BIG‑IP management IP/URL for that LB (on mgmt net):
e.g. https://10.10.0.25
Partitions to use:
one for control‑plane (optional),
one for applications per tenant / per Shoot (their choice).
VIP subnet / pool they’ll use for:
control‑plane VIPs,
application VIPs.
CMP LBaaS (CCP) API endpoint and auth:
e.g. https://ccp-api.airtelcloud.com
Credentials:
for CMP API (for our extension),
for BIG‑IP mgmt (for CIS).
You will encode these into your configuration/Secrets.

2. Platform setup (what you do once)
2.1 Deploy Gardener as usual
Gardener control‑plane in a Seed cluster.
OpenStack provider extension etc. as normal.
2.2 Deploy the F5 Gardener extension in the Seed
You deploy our gardener-extension-f5 controller and create an F5LoadBalancerConfig CR that says:

spec:
  # Control-plane via CMP
  ccpApiEndpoint: "https://ccp-api.airtelcloud.com"
  tenantOrPartition: "tenant1-cp"
  credentialsSecretRef:
    name: cmp-lbaas-credentials
    namespace: garden-f5-system
  controlPlaneVIP: "203.0.113.10"   # CP VIP CMP allocated for this tenant/shoot set

  # Application plane via CIS talking to BIG-IP mgmt IP
  enableApplicationLB: true
  cis:
    image: "f5networks/k8s-bigip-ctlr:<tag>"
    bigipUrl: "https://10.10.0.25"  # BIG-IP mgmt IP from CMP
    partition: "tenant1-app"
    extraArgs: []

CMP/cloud team chooses/allocates controlPlaneVIP from the VIP pool and tells you.
bigipUrl is the management IP they give for that LB.
2.3 DNS and certs
Agree how api.<shoot>.<domain> will map to the controlPlaneVIP.
Decide where TLS terminates (BIG‑IP vs apiserver).
3. What happens when a new Kubernetes cluster (Shoot) is created
A tenant/customer requests a cluster via Gardener (or your portal). Gardener creates a Shoot. Now the automation kicks in.

3.1 Control‑plane load balancing (kube‑apiserver)
Gardener F5 extension is triggered (in Seed)

For that Shoot it:

Reads F5LoadBalancerConfig and CMP creds.
Discovers the kube‑apiserver endpoints in the Seed:
IP:port list of apiserver Pods.
Calls CMP LBaaS API

Sends to ccpApiEndpoint:

“Create/Update a Virtual Server on VIP 203.0.113.10:443 with these backends.”

CMP LBaaS:

checks its DB,
programs F5 via its own internal “F5 LBaaS client”:
create pool with apiserver backends,
create monitor,
create Virtual Server on that VIP.
Updates status

Stores VS ID/name from CMP,
Marks control‑plane LB as Ready.
What the tenant sees for control plane

They get a kubeconfig pointing to https://api.<shoot>.<domain> → 203.0.113.10.
Path:
Tenant → DNS → controlPlaneVIP (203.0.113.10) → F5 → apiserver Pods.
You don’t care about self IPs / floating self IPs; CMP already made F5 HA

3.2 Application load balancing (inside the Shoot, via CIS)
Now we enable apps to get external VIPs.

F5 extension deploys CIS into the Shoot

In the Shoot cluster, using the Shoot kubeconfig, it creates:

ServiceAccount + ClusterRole + ClusterRoleBinding for CIS.

bigip-login Secret with BIG‑IP creds.

CIS Deployment:

image from spec.cis.image,

args like:

--bigip-url=https://10.10.0.25
--bigip-partition=tenant1-app-or-<shoot-partition>
...

Waits until CIS Pods are Ready.

Tenant deploys an application

Inside the Shoot, tenant applies:
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: my-app-svc
spec:
  type: LoadBalancer
  ports:
    - port: 80
      targetPort: 8080
  selector:
    app: my-app

(Or an Ingress backed by such a Service.)

CIS sees this Service

Watches the Shoot API.
Sees Service type=LoadBalancer (and/or Ingress).
Reads its endpoints (Pod IPs / NodePorts on worker nodes).
CIS talks to BIG‑IP mgmt IP

Uses --bigip-url=https://10.10.0.25.

Calls BIG‑IP REST API to:

Ask CMP/F5 (per policy) to allocate a VIP from the VIP subnet for this Service.
Create:
pool with backend Pods,
monitor,
Virtual Server on that new app VIP.
(Exact “allocate VIP” vs “you specify VIP” behaviour is driven by CMP/BIG‑IP config, but from your side it’s just CIS → BIG‑IP.)

CIS writes VIP back to the Service

The Service status becomes:

status:
  loadBalancer:
    ingress:
      - ip: "203.0.113.20"   # app VIP

What the tenant sees for apps

They run kubectl get svc my-app-svc and see EXTERNAL-IP = 203.0.113.20.
They point their application DNS (e.g. shop.example.com) to 203.0.113.20.
Path:
Client → DNS → app VIP (203.0.113.20) → F5 → Shoot worker/pods.
Autoscaling and node changes:

When Pods or nodes change, Kubernetes Endpoints change.
CIS sees this and updates the pool members on BIG‑IP automatically.
No manual work.

4. Summary: “how do we start, what do we get?”
Start

Ask CMP team to:

Provision an F5 LB instance for your env/tenant,
Give you:
BIG‑IP management IP (for CIS),
CCP/LBaaS API endpoint + creds (for control plane),
At least one control‑plane VIP from their VIP subnet,
Partition naming rules.
Deploy gardener-extension-f5 in the Seed with an F5LoadBalancerConfig that contains:

ccpApiEndpoint, controlPlaneVIP, CMP creds,
cis.bigipUrl (the mgmt IP) and CIS image/partition.
What you get, functionally

For each new Shoot:

Control‑plane LB is set up automatically:
kube‑apiserver behind controlPlaneVIP via CMP LBaaS.
Application LB is set up automatically:
CIS runs in the Shoot, talking to BIG‑IP mgmt IP,
Any Service type=LoadBalancer / Ingress gets its own app VIP on F5.
